<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What was the "Open Door Policy"?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Immigration policy</option>
            <option letter="b">Equal trade access to China</option>
            <option letter="c">Diplomatic relations with Japan</option>
            <option letter="d">Pacific island exploration</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Open Door Policy, announced in 1899, called for equal trading rights in China for all nations, preventing any one nation from monopolizing Chinese trade.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Who was John Hay?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">A military general</option>
            <option letter="b">Secretary of State</option>
            <option letter="c">Chinese diplomat</option>
            <option letter="d">Business leader</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>John Hay was Secretary of State under McKinley and Roosevelt, and authored the Open Door Notes establishing the Open Door Policy.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What prompted the U.S. to establish the Open Door Policy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Chinese request</option>
            <option letter="b">Fear of European dominance in China</option>
            <option letter="c">Military necessity</option>
            <option letter="d">Domestic pressure</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The U.S. established the Open Door Policy to prevent European powers from dividing China into exclusive spheres of influence.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How did European nations initially respond to the Open Door Policy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Immediate acceptance</option>
            <option letter="b">Qualified agreement</option>
            <option letter="c">Complete rejection</option>
            <option letter="d">Military threats</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>European powers gave qualified agreement to the Open Door Policy but didn't fully commit to following it.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was the main economic goal of the Open Door Policy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Colonize China</option>
            <option letter="b">Ensure equal trade opportunities</option>
            <option letter="c">Block all foreign trade</option>
            <option letter="d">Support Chinese industry</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The main economic goal was to ensure all nations had equal trade opportunities in China, preventing any single nation from monopolizing Chinese markets.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
